00:15:51,992 --> 00:15:55,913
Did Clarence get
the Alpine Shepherd Boy?

244
00:15:56,080 --> 00:15:57,831
<i>I'm sorry?</i>

245
00:15:58,999 --> 00:16:00,626
The Hummel.

246
00:16:00,793 --> 00:16:01,919
<i>Oh, the little figure.</i>

247
00:16:02,086 --> 00:16:04,296
<i>Yeah, yeah, he got it.</i>

248
00:16:04,463 --> 00:16:07,424
So he finished college, then?

249
00:16:07,591 --> 00:16:10,594
<i>Yep. Just this last semester.</i>

250
00:16:10,761 --> 00:16:12,930
Good. That's-- That's good.

251
00:16:13,097 --> 00:16:14,223
<i>How did you know?</i>

252
00:16:14,390 --> 00:16:16,809
<i>Oh, because you did the will. Right.</i>

253
00:16:18,602 --> 00:16:20,729
Is there a memorial?

254
00:16:20,896 --> 00:16:22,982
<i>Oh, sorry. It was last week.</i>

255
00:16:23,816 --> 00:16:27,778
<i>Anyway, it's my busiest time at work,</i>
<i>and Angie's doing the best she can...</i>

256
00:16:27,945 --> 00:16:29,822
<i>...but I have to get back to Salt Lake.</i>

257
00:16:29,989 --> 00:16:34,702
<i>Are you on an hourly rate or would</i>
<i>this be, like, a flat-fee kind of thing?</i>

258
00:16:38,288 --> 00:16:39,957
<i>Mr. McGill?</i>

259
00:16:40,833 --> 00:16:43,168
I'm sorry. I, uh....

260
00:16:44,044 --> 00:16:47,798
I'm not practicing any longer.

261
00:16:47,965 --> 00:16:49,717
<i>Oh, darn it.</i>

262
00:16:50,801 --> 00:16:53,053
I can refer you, though. Um....

263
00:16:55,097 --> 00:16:59,852
Hamlin Hamlin McGill has an excellent
estate law department...

264
00:17:00,019 --> 00:17:04,189
...and they'll help you sort things out.
Just ask for Francis Scheff.

265
00:17:04,356 --> 00:17:06,233
He'll point you in the right direction.

266
00:17:06,400 --> 00:17:08,610
<i>Hamlin Hamlin McGill.</i>

267
00:17:08,777 --> 00:17:11,989
<i>McGill? Wait, isn't that you?</i>

268
00:17:12,281 --> 00:17:14,908
Ah, it's just a coincidence.

269
00:17:15,617 --> 00:17:17,953
<i>All right, well, thank you, Mr. McGill.</i>

270
00:17:18,120 --> 00:17:19,580
You bet.

271
00:17:22,207 --> 00:17:24,001
Goddamn it.

272
00:17:37,848 --> 00:17:38,932
[TV BEEPS]

273
00:17:39,099 --> 00:17:42,644
WOMAN [ON TV]: <i>My husband and I</i>
<i>scrimped and saved for so many years.</i>

274
00:17:42,811 --> 00:17:45,731
<i>We did our best to build a nest egg</i>
<i>so that we wouldn't be...</i>

275
00:17:45,898 --> 00:17:47,858
<i>...a burden to our family.</i>

276
00:17:48,025 --> 00:17:51,737
<i>After Ronald passed,</i>
<i>I moved to an assisted-living facility...</i>

277
00:17:51,904 --> 00:17:53,489
<i>...a nice place.</i>

278
00:17:53,655 --> 00:17:56,366
<i>They told me</i>
<i>they'd take care of everything.</i>

279
00:17:56,533 --> 00:17:59,828
<i>But then one day</i>
<i>they said all my money was gone.</i>

280
00:18:00,037 --> 00:18:02,206
<i>How could that be?</i>

281
00:18:02,372 --> 00:18:04,208
<i>Where did it all go?</i>

282
00:18:04,374 --> 00:18:07,586
JIMMY [ON TV]:<i> If you or a loved one is a</i>
<i>resident of a Sandpiper Crossing facility...</i>

283
00:18:07,753 --> 00:18:08,796
[PHONE BUZZING]

284
00:18:08,962 --> 00:18:11,173
<i>...or other associated</i>
<i>retirement community...</i>

285
00:18:11,340 --> 00:18:14,051
<i>...you may be eligible to receive</i>
<i>compensation for a--</i>

286
00:18:14,218 --> 00:18:15,427
[TV TURNS OFF]

287
00:18:17,262 --> 00:18:19,348
-Hey there.
KIM: <i>Hey.</i>

288
00:18:19,515 --> 00:18:21,141
<i>Guess where I am?</i>

289
00:18:21,308 --> 00:18:22,559
Somewhere good?

290
00:18:22,726 --> 00:18:24,937
<i>Somewhere very good.</i>

291
00:18:25,104 --> 00:18:26,980
<i>You could be here too.</i>

292
00:18:48,794 --> 00:18:52,131
-Hey there.
-Hey, Giselle.

293
00:18:52,339 --> 00:18:56,343
Heh, heh. I was thinking we could just be
Kim and Jimmy today.

294
00:18:56,510 --> 00:18:58,595
Ah. Okay.

295
00:18:58,762 --> 00:19:00,264
Those two aren't all bad.

296
00:19:01,098 --> 00:19:03,600
Rumors and hearsay. How's work?

297
00:19:04,852 --> 00:19:06,395
It is a job.

298
00:19:06,562 --> 00:19:09,273
And how about you? Work's good?

299
00:19:09,439 --> 00:19:12,109
Yeah, actually. I have news.

300
00:19:12,276 --> 00:19:15,237
Good news. It's great news, really.

301
00:19:15,404 --> 00:19:19,074
It could change things
for Wexler-McGill.

302
00:19:19,241 --> 00:19:22,953
But I met with Rich Schweikart today.

303
00:19:23,120 --> 00:19:24,538
-Really?
-Yeah.

304
00:19:24,705 --> 00:19:27,791
Well, they took on Gatwood,
so I've been meaning to follow up.

305
00:19:27,958 --> 00:19:30,711
And, anyway, we were talking...

306
00:19:30,878 --> 00:19:33,422
...and he offered me a job.

307
00:19:33,714 --> 00:19:34,923
Again?

308
00:19:35,090 --> 00:19:37,885
What, he can't take no for an answer?

309
00:19:38,177 --> 00:19:40,804
They want me
to run their banking division.

310
00:19:40,971 --> 00:19:43,348
Build it, really.

311
00:19:43,557 --> 00:19:45,767
You're not seriously considering it?

312
00:19:46,435 --> 00:19:49,062
I'd be coming in as a partner.

313
00:19:49,438 --> 00:19:53,192
But I thought things were going okay
with Mesa Verde since, uh--

314
00:19:53,358 --> 00:19:55,319
They are. They were.

315
00:19:55,611 --> 00:19:59,239
My workload has gotten
a lot more complicated lately.

316
00:19:59,448 --> 00:20:03,744
I've been taking on some pro bono work.
Overflow from the public defender's office.

317
00:20:03,911 --> 00:20:07,998
PD overflow? When did you--? Why...?

318
00:20:11,710 --> 00:20:13,128
I like it.

319
00:20:14,504 --> 00:20:16,465
I'm good at it.

320
00:20:16,673 --> 00:20:20,886
And I'm helping people, Jimmy.

321
00:20:21,053 --> 00:20:25,599
I know that sounds cheesy.
It's whatever, but it's the truth.

322
00:20:26,099 --> 00:20:29,519
No, it makes a lot of sense.

323
00:20:33,148 --> 00:20:37,402
I have been thinking
about criminal law myself lately.

324
00:20:37,569 --> 00:20:40,697
You know,
for when I get my license back.

325
00:20:41,448 --> 00:20:42,699
Really?

326
00:20:42,866 --> 00:20:45,077
Yeah. You know, like you said...

327
00:20:45,244 --> 00:20:47,955
...you know, you're helping people.

328
00:20:49,414 --> 00:20:53,585
I'm thinking an office in one of these
refurbished bungalows, you know...

329
00:20:53,752 --> 00:20:57,881
...downtown by the courts. Stick around
where all the people who need help are.

330
00:20:59,383 --> 00:21:02,302
Boy. It has a nice ring to it now.

331
00:21:02,469 --> 00:21:05,639
Wexler-McGill, criminal law.

332
00:21:07,140 --> 00:21:09,685
That all sounds great.

333
00:21:11,186 --> 00:21:13,105
The thing is...

334
00:21:13,563 --> 00:21:16,108
...if I go to Schweikart & Cokely...

335
00:21:16,275 --> 00:21:19,569
...I have all those associates
to help cover Mesa Verde.

336
00:21:20,696 --> 00:21:22,447
It'll keep paying the bills...

337
00:21:22,614 --> 00:21:26,034
...and free me up to do the work
I really care about.

338
00:21:29,705 --> 00:21:32,958
So you'd kind of get to have
your cake and eat it too.

339
00:21:34,293 --> 00:21:36,128
Kind of, yeah.

340
00:21:37,004 --> 00:21:38,130
[SIGHS]

341
00:21:42,801 --> 00:21:44,303
I'll be right back.

342
00:21:44,511 --> 00:21:46,638
-No, Jimmy.
-What? I-- No, I just--

343
00:21:46,805 --> 00:21:48,724
I gotta hit the head.

344
00:21:52,686 --> 00:21:54,688
[CHOPPING]

345
00:21:55,397 --> 00:21:56,648
[SIGHS]

346
00:21:56,898 --> 00:21:58,900
[CHOPPING CONTINUES]

347
00:22:18,795 --> 00:22:20,797
[INDISTINCT CHATTER]

348
00:22:23,884 --> 00:22:24,968
I say do it.

349
00:22:26,261 --> 00:22:29,639
It's a great opportunity
and you should jump on it.

350
00:22:31,433 --> 00:22:32,934
-You mean that?
-Yeah.

351
00:22:33,977 --> 00:22:36,605
Kim, you gotta do what's best for you.

352
00:22:37,022 --> 00:22:38,732
You sure?

353
00:22:39,649 --> 00:22:41,026
Yes.

354
00:22:41,193 --> 00:22:44,404
I can't ask you to wait around for me.

355
00:22:44,863 --> 00:22:46,156
And who knows?

356
00:22:46,323 --> 00:22:49,326
Ten months, a lot can happen.

357
00:22:49,534 --> 00:22:52,371
Yeah. Yeah. Who knows?

358
00:22:52,621 --> 00:22:57,209
Yeah, so to Schweikart and Cokely,
and Wexler.

359
00:23:41,795 --> 00:23:43,296
Hi.

360
00:23:43,505 --> 00:23:45,006
Hi.

361
00:23:48,051 --> 00:23:50,762
I only have a few minutes.
I have to pick Kaylee up.

362
00:23:52,013 --> 00:23:53,473
Okay.

363
00:23:56,518 --> 00:23:58,979
What did you want to tell me, Mike?

364
00:24:01,273 --> 00:24:03,191
I stand by what I said.

365
00:24:03,358 --> 00:24:05,026
The guy's a charlatan.

366
00:24:05,193 --> 00:24:09,156
But there's a time and there's a place,
and that wasn't it.

367
00:24:10,615 --> 00:24:11,992
STACEY:
Um....

368
00:24:12,826 --> 00:24:15,495
You left me quite the mess.

369
00:24:16,204 --> 00:24:18,123
Yeah, I can see that.

370
00:24:19,708 --> 00:24:20,959
[STACEY SIGHS]

371
00:24:25,380 --> 00:24:28,550
It'll be okay, eventually.

372
00:24:30,927 --> 00:24:33,763
Anita's not happy.
You might wanna call her.

373
00:24:35,056 --> 00:24:37,350
Probably better if I don't.

374
00:24:39,060 --> 00:24:43,273
You know that I would
never forget Matty.

375
00:24:45,484 --> 00:24:47,152
I know.

376
00:24:48,028 --> 00:24:51,781
No one expects you to wear
a hair shirt for the rest of your life.

377
00:24:52,115 --> 00:24:53,825
Same goes for you.

378
00:24:53,992 --> 00:24:56,161
You and Kaylee okay?

379
00:24:57,078 --> 00:24:58,705
We're good.

380
00:24:59,789 --> 00:25:02,334
Then I'm good.

381
00:25:04,961 --> 00:25:07,756
I was thinking...

382
00:25:07,923 --> 00:25:10,842
...maybe I could pick
Kaylee up from school tomorrow?

383
00:25:13,845 --> 00:25:17,057
Yeah, that'd be a big help, Pop.

384
00:25:20,727 --> 00:25:21,811
See you then.

385
00:25:22,979 --> 00:25:24,356
Okay.

386
00:25:41,248 --> 00:25:43,250
[INDISTINCT CHATTER]

387
00:25:44,668 --> 00:25:46,586
You can go in, Jimmy.
He's expecting you.

388
00:25:46,753 --> 00:25:48,713
JIMMY:
Thanks, Julie.

389
00:25:50,340 --> 00:25:51,591
[JIMMY SIGHS]

390
00:25:52,175 --> 00:25:54,010
Oh, hey, Jimmy.

391
00:25:54,177 --> 00:25:55,470
Howard.

392
00:25:55,637 --> 00:25:58,265
This was going in the mail.
You would've got it Friday.

393
00:25:58,431 --> 00:26:02,352
Yeah. I got a pressing need
only $5000 will cure.

394
00:26:02,602 --> 00:26:04,354
Oh. There you go, then.

395
00:26:05,730 --> 00:26:07,315
Everything correct?

396
00:26:07,524 --> 00:26:09,734
-Looks good. Thanks.
-Of course.

397
00:26:09,901 --> 00:26:14,072
Hey, I see a lot of empty cubicles
out there. What's going on?

398
00:26:15,365 --> 00:26:17,701
We're doing some reorganizing.

399
00:26:18,159 --> 00:26:21,663
Just making the office
a little more feng shui, I take it?

400
00:26:22,247 --> 00:26:23,999
We've had some setbacks.

401
00:26:25,083 --> 00:26:27,836
Paying out to Chuck's estate?

402
00:26:28,795 --> 00:26:30,255
That is part of it.

403
00:26:32,465 --> 00:26:34,301
And to be frank...

404
00:26:34,676 --> 00:26:37,262
...the firm's reputation is...

405
00:26:37,429 --> 00:26:38,555
...not what it was.

406
00:26:39,556 --> 00:26:41,308
So, what's the plan?

407
00:26:41,474 --> 00:26:45,604
The consultants call it "rightsizing."

408
00:26:46,313 --> 00:26:51,318
No, I mean, what's the plan
to get HHM back on its feet?

409
00:26:51,568 --> 00:26:52,736
[SIGHS]

410
00:27:06,875 --> 00:27:10,211
Are you kidding me?
I just referred a client to you guys.

411
00:27:10,670 --> 00:27:13,882
You're welcome, by the way.
You tell me this place is falling apart?

412
00:27:14,049 --> 00:27:15,925
Get your shit together, Howard.

413
00:27:16,635 --> 00:27:18,136
-Excuse me?
-Oh, please.

414
00:27:18,303 --> 00:27:22,349
You suffer one little setback and
you're gonna let your entire legacy go?

415
00:27:22,515 --> 00:27:26,269
-One little setback?
-Fine, your pain is very special.

416
00:27:26,436 --> 00:27:28,521
Woe is you. Just stop wallowing.

417
00:27:28,730 --> 00:27:31,066
Okay? This place is all you've got.

418
00:27:31,274 --> 00:27:34,986
That and your hair, which, let's face it,
the clock's ticking there too, so....

419
00:27:35,153 --> 00:27:37,906
You wanna save your business?
You wanna save your dignity?

420
00:27:38,073 --> 00:27:40,950
You're gonna have to fight. Hey.

421
00:27:41,493 --> 00:27:43,328
You're a shitty lawyer, Howard.

422
00:27:44,371 --> 00:27:46,289
But you're a great salesman.

423
00:27:46,581 --> 00:27:48,875
So get out there and sell.

424
00:27:49,751 --> 00:27:51,044
Fuck you, Jimmy.

425
00:27:51,252 --> 00:27:54,005
There you go. Use that.

426
00:27:54,464 --> 00:27:56,883
[♪♪♪]

427
00:27:58,635 --> 00:27:59,803
JIMMY:
It's $4000.

428
00:28:01,805 --> 00:28:03,973
-Pleasure doing business.
-You as well.

429
00:28:04,182 --> 00:28:07,852
[♪♪♪]

430
00:28:08,061 --> 00:28:09,062
[LIFT WHIRRING]

431
00:28:31,793 --> 00:28:35,588
[♪♪♪]

432
00:29:14,043 --> 00:29:17,547
All set over here. You got a spot yet?

433
00:29:18,381 --> 00:29:21,551
Piñatas? Are you kidding?

434
00:29:22,594 --> 00:29:25,680
No, no, that could-- Could work, yeah.

435
00:29:25,847 --> 00:29:30,643
Regardless, we have full run
of the place? There's no prying eyes?

436
00:29:31,394 --> 00:29:34,272
All right. Well, that's it, then.

437
00:29:34,647 --> 00:29:36,733
Yeah, she's fine. Heh, heh.

438
00:29:38,109 --> 00:29:41,154
Yeah, I change half the water
in the tank every week.

439
00:29:41,321 --> 00:29:42,989
She's good.

440
00:29:43,156 --> 00:29:45,909
No, I know. Don't overfeed.

441
00:29:46,159 --> 00:29:48,328
All right. Goodbye.

442
00:29:49,788 --> 00:29:51,623
-What are you doing?
-Oh.

443
00:29:51,998 --> 00:29:53,666
Mrs. Nguyen.

444
00:29:53,833 --> 00:29:57,170
Just, you know,
step right on in anytime, you know?

445
00:29:57,378 --> 00:29:59,464
What's all this?

446
00:30:00,465 --> 00:30:02,175
It's a side business.

447
00:30:02,342 --> 00:30:04,427
I thought you were a lawyer.

448
00:30:04,594 --> 00:30:06,429
I've had a temporary setback.

449
00:30:06,846 --> 00:30:08,681
Lost your job again?

450
00:30:08,890 --> 00:30:11,142
Did you need something, Mrs. Nguyen?

451
00:30:11,518 --> 00:30:14,229
I don't want people coming in and out
to buy your stupid phones.

452
00:30:14,395 --> 00:30:16,856
I won't sell them out of the office,
so don't worry.

453
00:30:17,023 --> 00:30:18,525
You can't keep them here.

454
00:30:18,691 --> 00:30:21,569
I pay rent for this place.
I can do whatever I want with it.

455
00:30:21,736 --> 00:30:23,112
They're a fire hazard.

456
00:30:23,321 --> 00:30:26,449
Well, they're not gonna be here
very long, okay?

457
00:30:28,701 --> 00:30:29,744
Hmm.

458
00:30:29,953 --> 00:30:31,371
[SIGHS]

459
00:30:36,543 --> 00:30:38,920
That's-- That's on me.

460
00:30:39,087 --> 00:30:42,674
No, it's prepaid, 350 minutes.

461
00:30:46,553 --> 00:30:49,430
Get-rich-quick schemes never work.

462
00:30:50,557 --> 00:30:51,808
Just watch me.

463
00:30:51,975 --> 00:30:53,935
[NGUYEN SPEAKS IN VIETNAMESE]

464
00:30:56,729 --> 00:30:58,731
[OXYGEN MACHINE WHIRRING]

465
00:31:16,666 --> 00:31:19,961
The doctor tells me
your fever has gotten worse.

466
00:31:22,881 --> 00:31:25,675
They say this infection may kill you.

467
00:31:32,807 --> 00:31:34,893
Even if it doesn't...

468
00:31:35,685 --> 00:31:40,189
...my doctor tells me again and again
that you may never wake.

469
00:31:42,984 --> 00:31:44,903
And yet...

470
00:31:45,320 --> 00:31:46,905
...I wait.

471
00:32:02,462 --> 00:32:04,964
I grew up quite poor.

472
00:32:06,299 --> 00:32:08,509
We lived in the hills.

473
00:32:09,385 --> 00:32:13,640
In a place my brothers built
from things they found.

474
00:32:14,599 --> 00:32:17,518
Metal sheeting, plywood.

475
00:32:19,520 --> 00:32:22,774
When it rained, it smelled like hay.

476
00:32:25,735 --> 00:32:27,862
We were always hungry.

477
00:32:29,072 --> 00:32:31,574
But there was a lucuma tree.

478
00:32:32,075 --> 00:32:35,036
Scrawny. Barely alive.

479
00:32:35,453 --> 00:32:39,499
My family had given up on it
years before.

480
00:32:39,791 --> 00:32:41,751
Never bore fruit.

481
00:32:43,503 --> 00:32:45,421
When I was 7...

482
00:32:47,256 --> 00:32:49,550
...I became fixated on it.

483
00:32:50,343 --> 00:32:51,886
I watered it...

484
00:32:52,512 --> 00:32:54,305
...tended to it.

485
00:32:55,556 --> 00:32:57,725
It took a long time.

486
00:32:58,935 --> 00:33:02,689
But the buds grew into green fruit.

487
00:33:02,855 --> 00:33:04,732
I was so proud.

488
00:33:05,233 --> 00:33:06,609
I didn't tell anyone.

489
00:33:06,776 --> 00:33:09,696
I plucked one
and hid behind our shack.

490
00:33:09,862 --> 00:33:11,739
I ate the whole thing.

491
00:33:11,906 --> 00:33:16,285
I'd never tasted something so sweet.

492
00:33:16,828 --> 00:33:20,581
It was like caramel.

493
00:33:22,625 --> 00:33:25,628
At first, we ate the fruit ourselves.

494
00:33:25,795 --> 00:33:29,173
And then I began
taking it to the village to sell.

495
00:33:31,801 --> 00:33:35,596
One day, much of the fruit
was gone from my tree.

496
00:33:38,725 --> 00:33:42,729
Pieces were scattered on the ground,
half-eaten.

497
00:33:44,731 --> 00:33:49,318
I thought it was probably a coati.

498
00:33:50,778 --> 00:33:52,905
Have you ever seen one?

499
00:33:54,532 --> 00:33:58,578
About the size of a large housecat.

500
00:34:00,163 --> 00:34:01,998
Opportunists.

501
00:34:03,666 --> 00:34:05,501
I built a snare...

502
00:34:06,961 --> 00:34:09,255
...using branches and wire.

503
00:34:09,422 --> 00:34:12,675
It didn't take long
for the animal to set it off.

504
00:34:12,842 --> 00:34:15,511
But the coati thrashed so hard...

505
00:34:15,678 --> 00:34:18,181
...it broke out of the snare.

506
00:34:19,140 --> 00:34:22,643
Broke its leg as well.

507
00:34:23,019 --> 00:34:25,146
I tried to grab it...

508
00:34:25,563 --> 00:34:27,440
...but it slipped away.

509
00:34:27,607 --> 00:34:29,901
It ran under the house.

510
00:34:30,693 --> 00:34:35,031
I knew it would show itself
sooner or later.

511
00:34:36,783 --> 00:34:38,451
So I waited.

512
00:34:39,535 --> 00:34:41,496
For hours.

513
00:34:41,662 --> 00:34:43,748
Into the night.

514
00:34:46,125 --> 00:34:48,628
When my brothers called for me...

515
00:34:51,422 --> 00:34:53,132
...I did not answer.

516
00:34:53,299 --> 00:34:55,551
I didn't make a sound.

517
00:34:57,637 --> 00:34:59,555
I was so still.

518
00:35:03,059 --> 00:35:06,687
Finally, it came out.

519
00:35:07,480 --> 00:35:09,690
It knew I was there...

520
00:35:10,274 --> 00:35:12,318
...but it was hungry.

521
00:35:13,820 --> 00:35:15,696
This time...

522
00:35:15,863 --> 00:35:17,740
...I was ready.

523
00:35:18,616 --> 00:35:20,618
I caught it.

524
00:35:22,370 --> 00:35:24,580
It fought me...

525
00:35:25,998 --> 00:35:29,502
...but I was stronger.

526
00:35:34,257 --> 00:35:37,343
The merciful thing
would've been to kill it.

527
00:35:46,936 --> 00:35:49,063
I kept it.

528
00:35:50,857 --> 00:35:53,484
It lived for quite some time.

529
00:35:53,693 --> 00:35:55,069
[♪♪♪]

530
00:35:57,572 --> 00:36:02,785
I believe you will wake, Hector.

531
00:36:34,901 --> 00:36:36,152
Wow.

532
00:36:36,360 --> 00:36:37,653
[IN GERMAN]
This is huge.

533
00:36:37,820 --> 00:36:38,905
MAN 1 [IN ENGLISH]:
Crazy.

534
00:36:39,071 --> 00:36:41,866
MAN 2 [IN GERMAN]: I'm starving.
I hope there's something in the kitchen.

535
00:36:42,783 --> 00:36:45,161
MAN 3: You idiot, should've eaten
on the plane.

536
00:36:47,163 --> 00:36:49,040
MAN 4:
Is that a bar?

537
00:36:49,790 --> 00:36:51,167
It is. Wonder what's on tap.

538
00:36:51,584 --> 00:36:53,586
[SPEAKING IN GERMAN]

539
00:36:56,380 --> 00:36:58,799
MAN 5: We're here to work.
Why do we need a bar?

540
00:36:59,383 --> 00:37:00,843
Because we're here to work.

541
00:37:01,302 --> 00:37:02,720
[SPEAKS IN GERMAN]

542
00:37:03,554 --> 00:37:06,515
[MEN CHATTERING IN GERMAN]

543
00:37:06,682 --> 00:37:07,808
[SIGHS]

544
00:37:12,063 --> 00:37:14,065
[CHATTERING IN GERMAN
CONTINUES]

545
00:37:29,121 --> 00:37:33,584
All right, gentlemen,
we have a few things to go over here.

546
00:37:41,676 --> 00:37:42,885
That means you too.

547
00:37:44,971 --> 00:37:46,555
Kai.

548
00:37:48,975 --> 00:37:50,559
Over here, Kai.

549
00:37:51,435 --> 00:37:52,770
WERNER [IN GERMAN]:
Enough!

550
00:37:52,979 --> 00:37:56,190
For what they're paying you, you'll listen.

551
00:38:09,453 --> 00:38:12,290
We got four bedrooms
between the two houses.

552
00:38:12,665 --> 00:38:15,293
I leave it to you to figure out
the roommate situation.

553
00:38:15,459 --> 00:38:20,006
I assume you're all friends, I don't
really wanna hear about it if you aren't.

554
00:38:20,172 --> 00:38:22,842
Working kitchens, so you can cook
whatever you want.

555
00:38:23,009 --> 00:38:26,429
The refrigerator, the cabinets
are stocked with the essentials.

556
00:38:26,595 --> 00:38:32,310
There's a shopping list. Write down
whatever you need and we'll get it.

557
00:38:32,727 --> 00:38:34,562
There is a phone in each house.

558
00:38:34,729 --> 00:38:38,274
It goes directly to me or one of my guys.

559
00:38:38,441 --> 00:38:40,943
Anything you need, call.

560
00:38:41,319 --> 00:38:43,654
KAI [IN ENGLISH]:
So when do the girls get here?

561
00:38:51,454 --> 00:38:53,873
Anything within reason.

562
00:39:00,212 --> 00:39:02,423
Any more questions?

563
00:39:07,261 --> 00:39:11,098
All right, you've got some time to relax
and settle in.

564
00:39:11,599 --> 00:39:14,060
Work starts tomorrow night.

565
00:39:17,021 --> 00:39:18,647
WERNER [IN ENGLISH]:
Michael.

566
00:39:18,981 --> 00:39:20,649
They all are good boys.

567
00:39:20,816 --> 00:39:25,279
Once the work begins, they focus.
I'll see to it.

568
00:39:25,988 --> 00:39:29,116
What you've done here
is very impressive.

569
00:39:29,283 --> 00:39:31,744
-Thank you for that, Michael.
-Hey.

570
00:39:33,496 --> 00:39:36,207
If you need anything to make
this go better, let me know.

571
00:39:36,374 --> 00:39:38,417
I will, certainly.

572
00:39:46,967 --> 00:39:48,552
[DOOR BUZZES]

573
00:39:54,558 --> 00:39:56,644
[DOOR BUZZES]

574
00:40:18,999 --> 00:40:21,836
[MEN SPEAKING IN GERMAN
OVER SPEAKERS]

575
00:40:22,586 --> 00:40:24,713
-Hey, Mike.
-Hey.

576
00:40:34,974 --> 00:40:38,102
[MEN SPEAKING IN GERMAN
OVER SPEAKERS]

577
00:40:42,398 --> 00:40:43,566
Keep an eye on this one.

578
00:41:11,927 --> 00:41:13,387
Hey.

579
00:41:13,721 --> 00:41:14,930
JIMMY:
I come in peace.

580
00:41:15,347 --> 00:41:18,058
I'm just-- Just here to make a deal.

581
00:41:18,851 --> 00:41:20,436
What kind of deal?

582
00:41:20,603 --> 00:41:24,273
Look, fellas, we--
We got off on the wrong foot.

583
00:41:24,440 --> 00:41:27,067
I'm sure you saw me here
selling my wares and thought...

584
00:41:27,234 --> 00:41:31,155
...I was just some rube out
looking to score a quick buck...

585
00:41:31,322 --> 00:41:36,452
...and just begging to be rolled.
But, guys, I'm thinking long term.

586
00:41:36,619 --> 00:41:41,832
I see a real need in this community
for safe, affordable, untraceable phones...

587
00:41:41,999 --> 00:41:43,542
...and I'm ready to fill it.

588
00:41:43,709 --> 00:41:44,793
[ZANE SCOFFS]

589
00:41:44,960 --> 00:41:46,212
Wah, wah, wah.

590
00:41:46,378 --> 00:41:49,215
All right. All right, straight talk.

591
00:41:49,381 --> 00:41:54,094
I need to be able to sell my phones
without worrying about getting ripped off.

592
00:41:55,137 --> 00:41:59,558
I'm proposing if you let me sell
my phones without hassle, I cut you in.

593
00:41:59,725 --> 00:42:04,021
Say, a hundred bucks
every night that I'm out?

594
00:42:04,188 --> 00:42:07,983
And that's money
for literally doing nothing.

595
00:42:12,154 --> 00:42:14,657
Why wouldn't we just take all of it?

596
00:42:15,491 --> 00:42:20,538
Because I'm talking consistent,
reliable profits, you know?

597
00:42:20,704 --> 00:42:24,375
Sure, you can rip me off again,
take all that I've got.

598
00:42:24,542 --> 00:42:29,421
But then I stop selling,
and you lose a valuable revenue stream.

599
00:42:34,802 --> 00:42:36,762
Give me all you got. Now.

600
00:42:36,971 --> 00:42:39,932
I'm trying to make money
for all of us here. Just work with me.

601
00:42:40,099 --> 00:42:43,811
-Give.
-If you'd just expand your thinking a little.

602
00:42:43,978 --> 00:42:45,813
You talk too much.

603
00:42:45,980 --> 00:42:49,775
All right, all right.
We got a man of action.

604
00:42:49,984 --> 00:42:51,986
[♪♪♪]

605
00:43:12,172 --> 00:43:14,008
[BOYS LAUGHING]

606
00:43:17,428 --> 00:43:19,430
[PANTING]

607
00:43:20,139 --> 00:43:22,308
You should've taken the deal.

608
00:43:22,474 --> 00:43:26,103
You're, like, the stupidest person
I've ever met.

609
00:43:26,312 --> 00:43:28,022
[GUN COCKS]

610
00:43:31,025 --> 00:43:33,319
[MUMBLING]

611
00:43:57,343 --> 00:44:00,846
[BAT SCRAPING ON FLOOR]

612
00:44:11,774 --> 00:44:13,442
[BOYS GRUNTING]

613
00:44:18,322 --> 00:44:20,324
Didn't know I had friends, did you?

614
00:44:22,951 --> 00:44:24,828
So, what's it gonna be? Fast or slow?

615
00:44:24,995 --> 00:44:27,373
It's gonna hurt like a bitch either way.

616
00:44:27,581 --> 00:44:28,832
[ROCCO GRUNTING]

617
00:44:28,999 --> 00:44:32,336
What was that? Was it slow?

618
00:44:33,253 --> 00:44:35,964
-Let me....
-Ah!

619
00:44:37,007 --> 00:44:38,967
We're sorry, man, all right? We're sorry.

620
00:44:41,053 --> 00:44:42,846
Yeah, you are. Very much so.

621
00:44:43,013 --> 00:44:45,683
We'll leave you alone.
We won't mess with you anymore.

622
00:44:45,891 --> 00:44:47,643
Easy to say now.
What about tomorrow?

623
00:44:47,810 --> 00:44:50,646
I-- I'll swear, man.
I'll swear on anything you want me to.

624
00:44:53,065 --> 00:44:56,402
-Cross your heart and hope to die?
-Yes. Yes, man.

625
00:44:58,487 --> 00:44:59,530
You mean it?

626
00:44:59,697 --> 00:45:01,907
Yes. Yes.

627
00:45:02,074 --> 00:45:05,077
Look, after this,
you'll never have to see us again.

628
00:45:05,703 --> 00:45:08,205
And you will spread the word
that I'm off-limits?

629
00:45:08,372 --> 00:45:10,666
Yes, yes, yes. We’ll tell everyone.

630
00:45:10,833 --> 00:45:14,378
We'll say don't-- Don't--
Don't mess with the cell phone guy.

631
00:45:16,630 --> 00:45:18,632
All right. We're done.

632
00:45:19,174 --> 00:45:20,217
We're done.

633
00:45:23,220 --> 00:45:24,847
I think they get it.

634
00:45:26,849 --> 00:45:28,517
Seriously, guys, we're done.

635
00:45:28,809 --> 00:45:32,104
Okay, we're good. All right?
That's enough.

636
00:45:32,521 --> 00:45:35,482
I appreciate the enthusiasm...

637
00:45:35,649 --> 00:45:37,735
-...but they got the message.
ROCCO: That's right.

638
00:45:37,901 --> 00:45:40,696
Listen to what he says.
I got the message.

639
00:45:40,863 --> 00:45:43,574
All right, you know what,
if it's that important to you...

640
00:45:43,782 --> 00:45:46,410
-...go ahead.
-No, no, no. Please.

641
00:45:47,745 --> 00:45:49,872
No, no, please, please.

642
00:45:50,247 --> 00:45:52,666
No, no, no. Please. Please, no!

643
00:46:14,062 --> 00:46:16,231
You get one warning.

644
00:46:16,398 --> 00:46:18,776
And that was it.

645
00:46:19,234 --> 00:46:20,360
[BAT CLATTERS]

646
00:46:32,873 --> 00:46:34,875
[♪♪♪]
